"></div><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/when-you-and-ai-become-bffs-ecbcda1e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">人工智能</a>生成的专业头像在年轻工作者中<a href="https://www.wsj.com/video/series/joanna-stern-personal-technology/extreme-makeover-ai-edition-testing-four-apps-that-distort-reality/EA3F97F6-7344-4679-97BF-5A712253E1C6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">很流行</a>。但一些有色人种女性表示，这项技术对她们来说效果不佳，会淡化肤色、搞乱发型并改变面部形状。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/85892a46-d385-4b3f-90a2-156518a2d8dd.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>王说，她的结果令人惊讶，因为她要求该程序“为原始照片中的女孩提供一张专业的 LinkedIn 个人资料照片”。</p><p> “整体效果肯定让我看起来像个白人，”亚裔美国人王说。</p><p> Playground AI 的创始人 Suhail Doshi 表示，该服务并非旨在用于专业爆头照片：“如果人们使用我们来做这件事，他们将会感到失望。”</p><h3>身体和面部扭曲</h3><p>随着简历和专业社交媒体资料开始变得<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/resumes-are-starting-to-look-like-instagramand-sometimes-even-tinder-11565707364?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">更像 Instagram</a> ，许多员工正在尝试制作完美的头像。预约专业摄影师拍摄照片并确保发型和化妆是顶级的，花费很容易就<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/perfect-linkedin-profile-headshot-photo-is-worth-1-000-and-a-job-11660160047?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">超过 1,000 美元。</a></p><p>只需花费 12 至 50 美元，人们就可以将自己的照片（包括自拍照）上传到各种<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/softbank-posts-another-loss-despite-technology-share-rebound-703975d1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">人工智能平台</a>。据人工智能创始人介绍，这些人工智能模型随后会根据上传的照片以及数以百万计的其他图像以及与他们接受训练的文本描述配对的图像，在专业环境中创建类似于用户的图像。</p><p>问题是，许多黑人、拉丁裔和亚洲女性表示，人工智能照片失败的情况超出了有据可查的技术失误，比如给一个人<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/reality-is-broken-we-have-ai-photos-to-blame-de00b23?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">太多牙齿或一只手上超过五个手指</a>。</p><p> Danielle DeRuiter-Williams 是一位来自新奥尔良的 38 岁多元化、公平和包容性专家，她使用了一项名为 AI SuitUp 的服务。她说，令她惊讶的是人工智能生成的照片缩小了她的鼻子并提亮了她的皮肤。</p><p> “这比任何事情都更滑稽，”她说。 “这只是向我展示了许多这项技术还处于萌芽阶段，尤其是它对非白人的适应性。”</p><p> AI SuitUp 创始人 Simon Restelli 表示，种族和性别偏见已融入许多人工智能平台使用的基础技术中。例如，AI SuitUp 等平台所培训的许多医生的在线照片往往都是男性。如果不进行进一步的细化，这些照片将会扭曲人工智能生成的照片的结果。他说，需要更多地关注输入到像 Restelli 这样的公司所建立的模型中的数据和照片，并补充说，随着消费者要求更好的产品，这种情况已经发生了。</p><p> “我相信社会会更加关注，”他说。</p><h3>糟糕的黑色发型</h3><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/80544616-8f84-429b-8c88-de026c3fe021.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> “这项技术推出时，似乎确实没有考虑到黑人，”她说。</p><p> Secta Labs 创始人 Marko Jak 表示，他的公司正在努力纠正人工智能问题。 Secta Labs 最近推出了新版本的技术，允许用户在创建帐户时识别自己的种族。他说，这样一来，人工智能就可以从更狭窄的、针对特定种族的基础模型中提取出人们的头像。</p><p> “你不能说，‘我的客户是专业人士，但肤色不是这样，’对吧？这简直是​​搞砸了，”他说。</p><p>杰克定期监控客户发布的有关其结果的社交媒体帖子。杰克和他的几位客户表示，当客户体验不佳时，他经常会向他们收集更多反馈，并提供退款或免费提供新头像。</p><p>索菲亚·卡特 (Sophia Carter) 是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/FDX" class="">联邦快递</a>驻北卡罗来纳州罗利市的劳动力策略师<span class="company-name-type">，</span></p>她说她最近在 Secta Labs 获得了积极的体验。尽管人工智能没有正确生成卡特姐妹辫（一种由数百个小辫子组成的发型），但她表示，她对结果中的各种其他黑人发型感到满意，包括玉米辫、爆炸头和扭发。卡特说，她至少获得了 100 张“可用的、令人惊叹的爆头照片”。 <p></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/54698132-0752-4dc0-940f-4d52ec7d10e7.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>哈里斯用她的结果向网上的其他人展示了她的经历，但没有人被选为个人资料照片。她现在计划投资数百美元请摄影师进行专业头像拍摄，而不是依赖人工智能工具。</p><h3>根本问题</h3><p>Vera 公司首席执行官 Liz O&#39;Sullivan 表示，人工智能图像生成器通常使用由互联网上的“大量数据”组成的基础模型，这些模型反映并延续了人们历史上的种族和性别偏见。帮助人工智能公司控制他们想要使用的模型的行为。她说，简单地反映互联网上的内容可能会产生一些有色人种得到的古怪结果。</p><p> “如果你不花时间、精力和金钱来管理你的训练数据并弄清楚这些相关性是否存在，那么你就会得到你投入的东西。这就是事情出错的原因，”奥沙利文说。</p><p>奥沙利文表示，虽然不可能消除人为偏见，但公司对抗渗透到其产品中的偏见的一种方法是定期手动更新这些平台训练的数据。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B00854AA-74DE-4E8C-8067-E09A4C38D821&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fgenerative-ai-photos-race-women-headshots-e60a8a3&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">在全国范围内，人工智能聊天机器人现在正在接受快餐得来速订单。 《华尔街日报》的乔安娜·斯特恩 (Joanna Stern) 在 Hardee&#39;s 对该技术进行了一系列测试，包括发出狗吠声和提出一些疯狂的问题。<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>许多人工智能图像生成服务使用的一种开源基础模型由 Stability AI 拥有。包括 Jak 和 Restelli 在内的几位人工智能服务创始人表示，Stability AI 的模型似乎使用了延续种族和其他偏见的数据集。</p><p>该公司表示正在努力解决这些偏见。其模型的最新版本于 7 月 26 日发布，应该可以提高所有种族和民族背景的人的图像准确性。该公司表示，这种名为 SDXL 1.0 的新模型可以生成色彩、灯光和阴影更加鲜艳和精确的图像。</p><p>公司发言人在一份书面声明中表示：“所有人工智能模型都存在固有偏差，这些偏差代表了它们所训练的数据集。” “我们打算针对不同国家和文化的特定数据集训练开源模型，这将有助于减轻一般数据集中因代表性过高而造成的偏差。”</p><p><em>图片来源：Rona Wang、Playground AI、Nathalie Walton、Christine Coakley Photography、Secta Labs、Nicole Harris、Secta Labs</em></p><p>写信给凯蒂·莫格<a href="mailto:katie.mogg@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">katie.mogg@wsj.com</a></p><p id="correction" class="correction"><strong>更正和放大</strong><br>即使哈里斯不是印度教徒，妮可·哈里斯使用人工智能生成的一些头像中也添加了宾迪。本文的早期版本错误地表示她不是印地语。 （8月8日更正）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 14:27:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/generative-ai-photos-race-women-headshots-e60a8a3</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/generative-ai-photos-race-women-headshots-e60a8a3<author><![CDATA[Katie Mogg]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>技术</category><category>人工智能/机器学习</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The AI Frenzy Resurrects the Old SoftBank]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>科技行业的低迷并没有让软银受到长期的打击。随着新牛市的到来，过度繁荣的迹象已经重新出现。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001118232"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831514?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">在科技股上涨的推动下，软银股价今年上涨了 24%。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Noriko Hayashi/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001118232"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jacky-wong" itemprop="url" rel="author">黄学友</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 8 日上午 9:18 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-ai-frenzy-resurrects-the-old-softbank-1bca01f7"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/JP/XTKS/9434" class="company-name">软银</a>再次发起攻势。许多长期投资者可能带着不小的恐惧看待这一前景。</p><p>该银行（包括其愿景基金）上季度向初创企业和其他公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/softbank-posts-another-loss-despite-technology-share-rebound-703975d1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">投资了 18 亿美元</a>，而前三个季度每个季度<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/softbank-turns-big-seller-after-tech-rout-b816b988?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">仅投资了约 5 亿美元</a>。这与软银的鼎盛时期相去甚远，当时该公司可以轻松地在一个季度内支出超过 100 亿美元，但仍然代表着明显的战略变化。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831543?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>人工智能的新热潮是原因之一。软银首席执行官孙正义 (Masayoshi Son) 在 6 月份发表了感人至深的讲话，表示他希望公司能够引领人工智能革命，据孙正义称，这是在经过一段时间的泪流满面、 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/softbanks-masayoshi-son-says-hes-focusing-on-ai-inventions-621089ac?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">深刻的自我反省</a>之后得出的启示。</p><p>软银已经从人工智能热潮中受益。在科技股上涨的推动下，该公司股价今年上涨了 24%。更具体地说，人们对人工智能的兴趣高涨，引发了人们<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/is-softbank-an-ai-stock-now-6e8dbfc7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">对芯片设计公司 Arm 更高估值</a>的希望，该公司正在进行首次公开​​募股。软银于 2016 年以 320 亿美元收购了这家英国公司。</p><p>但软银的实际盈利状况仍很糟糕。周二，软银公布了连续第三个季度的净亏损：截至 6 月份的三个月约为 33 亿美元。</p><p>科技股的反弹确实对其愿景基金业务有所帮助，该业务在经历了五个季度的亏损后恢复了约 4.26 亿美元的利润。但其中很大一部分来自软银控制的公司 12 亿美元的估值收益，主要是 Arm 和日本支付公司 PayPay。愿景基金业务拥有软银在这两家公司的部分股份。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=E8DCC2B0-F066-41EA-9053-96EC3A35B05E&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-ai-frenzy-resurrects-the-old-softbank-1bca01f7&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> 《华尔街日报》的阿萨·惠誉 (Asa Fitch) 详细分析了英伟达如何跻身市值 1 万亿美元的公司专属俱乐部。插图：赵安妮<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>即使考虑到这些收益，自 2017 年推出第一支基金以来，愿景基金部门的累计投资损失仍达 75 亿美元。</p><p>最近的两家初创公司的失败令人不受欢迎地提醒人们，软银此前曾一头扎进科技泡沫。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/zume-a-food-robotics-and-logistics-startup-cooks-up-2-25-billion-valuation-in-softbank-deal-1541099560?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">机器人披萨制作</a>和配送公司 Zume 和社交媒体应用程序 IRL 都已关门大吉。软银的现金注入帮助两家公司获得了令人垂涎的独角兽地位，跻身估值超过 10 亿美元的公司行列。软银刚刚对 IRL（意思是“现实生活中”）提起诉讼，指控该公司通过使用机器人来伪造其用户群。很多人都不会忽视其中的讽刺意义。<br>随着软银现在开始<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/he-spent-140-billion-on-ai-with-little-to-show-now-he-is-trying-again-dbcca17?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">拥抱人工智能狂欢</a>，更多此类事故可能是不可避免的。但无论好坏，这似乎都无法阻止孙正义或软银本身。</p><p>写信给 Jacky Wong： <a href="mailto:jacky.wong@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jacky.wong@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/642449b6-cdc9-47b1-a319-5f4da481a4d7.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 13:18:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-ai-frenzy-resurrects-the-old-softbank-1bca01f7</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-ai-frenzy-resurrects-the-old-softbank-1bca01f7<author><![CDATA[Jacky Wong]]></author><category>人工智能技术</category><category>电信服务</category><category>无线电信服务</category><category>移动通讯</category><category>技术</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>企业融资</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>企业家/初创公司</category><category>小企业启动资金</category><category>中小型企业</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>小企业融资</category><category>软银</category><category>9434.TO</category><category>日本：9434</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>企业融资</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>企业家</category><category>初创公司</category><category>小企业启动资金</category><category>小的</category><category>中型企业</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>小企业融资</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>电信服务</category><category>无线电信服务</category><category>移动电信</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[SoftBank Plans New AI Bets After First Investment Gains in 18 Months]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>尽管整体亏损，但科技板块的反弹令日本投资者更加大胆<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117716"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831445?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">软银首席执行官孙正义近日表示，他致力于人工智能领域。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Kiyoshi Ota/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117716"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/megumi-fujikawa" itemprop="url" rel="author">藤川惠</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 8 日上午 7:48（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/softbank-posts-another-loss-despite-technology-share-rebound-703975d1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>东京——<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/JP/XTKS/9984" class="company-name">软银集团</a>公布了一年半以来的首次投资收益，并表示将谨慎推进<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/he-spent-140-billion-on-ai-with-little-to-show-now-he-is-trying-again-dbcca17?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">人工智能相关领域的</a>新投资。</p><p>这家日本科技投资者报告称，其旗舰愿景基金部门在 4 月至 6 月这个季度获得了 10 亿美元的投资收益，首席财务官后藤义光 (Yoshimitsu Goto) 表示，这一结果鼓励该公司寻找新的资金存放处。</p><p>后藤在新闻发布会上谈到最近<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tech-stocks-meme-stocks-crypto-investors-are-feeling-bold-again-f158812b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">科技股的反弹时表示，“我希望科技创业领域的</a>潮流正在扭转”。</p><p>该公司表示，其愿景基金 1、愿景基金 2 和拉丁美洲基金中价值在最近一个季度增长的公司数量比上一季度几乎翻了一番，这是市场状况改善的迹象。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-ai-frenzy-resurrects-the-old-softbank-1bca01f7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">愿景基金部门本季度的投资</a>额为 18 亿美元，而前三个季度每个季度的投资额为 5 亿美元。这是该部门六个季度以来首次实现盈利。</p><p>总体而言，软银报告截至 6 月 30 日的季度净亏损 4776 亿日元，约合 33 亿美元。日元疲软导致该公司以美元计价的债务膨胀，而芯片设计公司 Arm 的收入因半导体行业放缓而下降。</p><p>在其持有的股票受到利率上升和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/softbank-loses-nearly-6-billion-in-quarter-as-investments-suffer-11675752219?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">全球科技股抛售的</a>严重打击后，该公司一直对进行新投资持谨慎态度。为了保留现金，它于今年早些时候完成了对中国电子商务公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BABA" class="company-name">阿里巴巴集团控股</a>公司股份的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/softbank-turns-big-seller-after-tech-rout-b816b988?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">出售</a>。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=E8DCC2B0-F066-41EA-9053-96EC3A35B05E&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fsoftbank-posts-another-loss-despite-technology-share-rebound-703975d1&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">芯片制造商英伟达跻身市值 1 万亿美元的公司专属俱乐部。 《华尔街日报》的 Asa Fitch 详细分析了 Nvidia 是如何实现这一目标的，以及人工智能为何推动该公司快速增长。插图：赵安妮<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>但随着科技行业的复苏，软银表示已准备好发起攻势，特别是在人工智能领域的投资。</p><p>周二，愿景基金首席执行官 Navneet Govil</p>表示Vision Fund 2仍有约80亿美元用于新投资。<p></p><p>首席执行官孙正义 (Masayoshi Son) 在 6 月份的公司年会上告诉股东，他<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/softbanks-masayoshi-son-says-hes-focusing-on-ai-inventions-621089ac?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">致力于人工智能</a>并经常通过与人工智能聊天机器人 ChatGPT 交谈来进行自己的发明。</p><p>后藤表示，软银在选择新投资时会更严格地关注其人工智能技术，因为有些人怀疑软银现有的投资是否真正以人工智能为中心。 Vision Fund 最近的一项投资是与英国初创公司 Tractable 达成的一项交易，该公司帮助保险公司使用人工智能处理索赔。</p><p>后藤表示<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/is-softbank-an-ai-stock-now-6e8dbfc7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，芯片设计公司 Arm</a>在美国上市的准备工作正在进行中，很快就会发布公告，但拒绝提供更多细节。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/d90969df-db3f-4890-9f4e-2892f502493a.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>写信给藤川惠<a href="mailto:megumi.fujikawa@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">megumi.fujikawa@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:48:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/softbank-posts-another-loss-尽管-technology-share-rebound-703975d1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/softbank-posts-another-loss-尽管-technology-share-rebound-703975d1<author><![CDATA[Megumi Fujikawa]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>电信服务</category><category>无线电信服务</category><category>移动通讯</category><category>技术</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>软银集团</category><category>9984.TO</category><category>日元：9984</category><category>后藤义光</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>电信服务</category><category>无线电信服务</category><category>移动电信</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[U.S.-Made Cluster Munitions Fuel Ukrainian Counteroffensive]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>炸弹正在摧毁基辅军队艰难推进地区的俄罗斯战壕和炮兵系统<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117870"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831501?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乌克兰斯拉维扬斯克郊区的一艘集束炸弹运输车。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Michal Burza/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117870"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ian-lovett" itemprop="url" rel="author">伊恩·洛维特</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name">尼基塔·尼古拉连科</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 8 日上午 7:23 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-made-cluster-munitions-fuel-ukrainian-counteroffensive-c45c305f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>乌克兰扎波罗热——在几周毫无进展之后，新交付的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-to-send-cluster-munitions-to-bolster-ukraines-fight-against-dug-in-russians-d2dd292f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国制造的集束弹药</a>为乌克兰夺回被俄罗斯占领的领土的行动注入了新的动力。</p><p>乌克兰士兵表示，他们使用集束炸弹袭击了俄罗斯步兵、车辆群和其他目标的集中区域，为地面进攻扫清了道路。集束炸弹可发射数十颗较小的子炸弹，比普通炮弹能在更大范围内造成破坏。</p><p>面对广阔的雷区和莫斯科优越的空中力量，基辅的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-stalled-offensive-puts-biden-in-uneasy-political-position-6f686ab5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">反攻行动一直举步维艰</a>，这阻碍了利用西方提供的坦克和装甲车大规模攻击和突破俄罗斯军队的防线。</p><p>虽然集束炸弹本身不会使战场力量平衡决定性地向有利于乌克兰的方向倾斜，但士兵们表示，它们帮助他们<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-adopts-slow-approach-to-counteroffensive-our-problem-everywhere-is-the-sky-a2e51d7a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">重新夺回了他们一直难以到达的俄罗斯阵地</a>。</p><p>这些弹药加上战术的改变，使乌克兰军队能够在某些地方推进到俄罗斯主要防线的打击距离内。这一进展伴随着巨大的伤亡。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=EDA02BF5-0836-4277-AB7C-10442F70192F&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fu-s-made-cluster-munitions-fuel-ukrainian-counteroffensive-c45c305f&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> 《华尔街日报》解释了集束弹药背后的技术以及它们为何引起人道主义担忧。插图：雅各布·亚历山大·尼尔森<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“集束炸弹很好。他们是有效的，”侦察连连长阿纳托利·哈琴科上尉说。 “但俄罗斯人挖得很深，而且学得很快。”</p><p>哈琴科说，俄罗斯的战壕可能有7英尺深，俄罗斯人正在通过更分散的兵力来适应，以避免重大损失。</p><p>最近扎波罗热市东南部Robobyne村周围的战斗证明了乌克兰军火库中新武器的有效性。</p><p> 7月下旬，一个排被困在村庄东边，遭受了俄罗斯的猛烈炮火。该部队通过无线电向指挥官发出请求，要求撤退。他告诉排要躲起来。集束炸弹飞过头顶。一名士兵说，他听到了类似下雨的声音，随后俄罗斯广播频道出现混乱。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1262" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/ad8ecb39-26bb-4a4d-b98b-c4700b367059-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> “他们大喊，‘我们有很多伤员。我们需要撤离。我们正在撤退，”乌克兰士兵说道。士兵们说，该排向前推进，占领了俄罗斯阵地。</p><p>乌克兰仍然没有达到俄罗斯最强大的防御、一系列战壕、坦克陷阱和其他障碍。军事专家表示，乌克兰可能需要<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/german-made-leopard-tanks-for-ukraine-are-politically-symbolic-but-no-game-changer-11674151572?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">豹2坦克</a>和其他西方提供的装甲车来突破这些防线。</p><p>为了保护这些车辆，乌克兰军方改变了战术，因为六月初乌克兰军队在雷区大量损失了这些车辆。现在，步兵在其他部队调来的预备队的支持下，正在步行穿过雷区，带领前进。</p><p>士兵们表示，随着战略变化，乌克兰军队现在相信他们有机会取得突破。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="2770" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/16d21f69-0148-4de6-8efa-d7313e2e8cf8-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>上周，33 岁的步兵列兵亚历山大 (Oleksandr) 所率领的 16 人排向俄罗斯阵地推进，遭到俄罗斯机枪的猛烈射击。乌克兰人被迫撤退。</p><p>然后乌克兰用集束弹药击中了隐藏俄罗斯军队的林木线。灌木丛和草着火了。当下一次攻击开始时，亚历山大可以看到他正在射击的俄罗斯人，他们不再隐藏在灌木丛中。</p><p>他的排占领了该阵地，杀死了大约 12 名俄罗斯人，并俘虏了另外几人。他说，囚犯们因集束炸弹而遭受脑震荡和烧伤。</p><p>他说：“使用集束炸弹，发射三枪，树木就会完全倒塌。”他补充说，集束炸弹袭击后，来袭的火力减少了。他说，由于这些弹药会造成大范围的破坏，因此它们不需要那么准确才能有效。</p><p> “即使你错过了一点，它仍然有效，”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831503?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">收集了去年袭击乌克兰哈尔科夫的俄罗斯火箭碎片，包括集束弹。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Libkos/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>美国驻欧洲陆军前司令本·霍奇斯中将表示，美国发送的是集束弹药，而不是更多的榴弹炮弹药，而<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-ramps-up-howitzer-shell-production-to-supply-ukraine-replenish-stockpiles-1e6dce54?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">西方国家的榴弹炮弹药已经不足</a>。他预计集束炸弹会更有效。它们是为一支寡不敌众的军队而设计的，就像现在的乌克兰一样。</p><p> “对付大规模编队的部分方法就是使用这种可分散的弹药，”他说。 “如果你坐在露天战壕中，你将为这些事情付出巨大的代价。”</p><p>最近发布在社交媒体上的视频显示，乌克兰集束弹药袭击后，俄罗斯士兵身上有六处小伤。霍奇斯表示，这些炸弹也符合他所认为的乌克兰针对俄罗斯火炮的战略转变。</p><p>他说：“只要炮兵能够到达，这些炮弹就能真正摧毁它们。”</p><p>这些武器被100多个国家禁止，美国向乌克兰运送这些武器的决定受到了人道主义组织的严厉批评。并非所有的小炸弹都会立即爆炸，有时它们还会伤害多年后遇到的人。</p><p>俄罗斯军队在整个战争期间一直在使用集束弹药：携带这些弹药的白色弹壳伸出全国各地的田野。据联合国报告称，乌克兰去年也曾多次使用过它们。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="610" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/b0723491-abf8-41f3-aadf-419194652de4-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>一名发射过集束弹药的炮兵部队士兵表示，这些弹药在战场上最为有效，因为它们分布在更广泛的区域。</p><p> “集束弹药很重要，但它们不是一个转折点，”他说，并补充说，针对不同情况使用不同类型的火炮很重要。</p><p>步兵表示，通常情况下，炮兵部队会在步行推进之前向俄罗斯阵地发射不同的弹药。尽管如此，Robotyne 的进步所付出的人力成本仍然是巨大的。</p><p> “我们正在用尸体在田野上排雷，”另一个新组建的、接受西方训练的旅的排长说。 “太糟糕了。”</p><p>步兵奥莱克桑德·佩尔辛 (Oleksandr Pershin) 表示，在罗布坦以东的田野里，集束弹药摧毁树木覆盖的能力是无价的。他说，在最近一次对俄罗斯阵地的攻击中，腰部高度以上的树已经没有了。</p><p> “其他一切都被摧毁了，”他说，“主要是集束弹药造成的。”</p><p>他说，一旦他的部队占据了这个位置，他们就试图继续穿过树林，向俄罗斯的下一条防线推进。在 24 小时内，他们进行了一系列攻击，但不断被击退，因为俄罗斯人用机枪扫射他们。</p><p>最终，他们被命令在原地挖战壕。</p><p>当 34 岁的 Pershin 正在挖掘时，一枚火箭落在他附近，弹片溅到他身上，把他送往医院。当他说话时，他的手臂上吊着绷带，全身的伤口都缠着绷带。他说，参与袭击的 60 人中有 45 人受伤或死亡。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=A74E51B6-FB53-4840-BB4D-2B1A0CCC986B&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fu-s-made-cluster-munitions-fuel-ukrainian-counteroffensive-c45c305f&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">官员称，俄罗斯周一对波克罗夫斯克镇发动袭击，造成至少 7 人死亡、80 多人受伤。罢工损坏了公寓、酒店、餐馆、商店和行政大楼。照片：Viacheslav Ratynskyi/Reuters<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p class="articleTagLine">——詹姆斯·马森对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Ian Lovett： <a href="mailto:ian.lovett@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ian.lovet@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:23:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-made-cluster-munitions-fuel-ukrainian-counteroffective-c45c305f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-made-cluster-munitions-fuel-ukrainian-counteroffective-c45c305f<author><![CDATA[Ian Lovett]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[After Feeding Explosion of Facial Recognition, China Moves to Rein It In]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>当局对何时使用该技术提出了限制，即使他们保留了国家安全例外情况<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117836"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831488?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">近年来，面部识别在中国的使用不断扩大。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Qilai Shen/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117836"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/karen-hao" itemprop="url" rel="author">郝凯伦</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/liza-lin" itemprop="url" rel="author">林丽莎</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 8 日上午 7:07 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-drafts-rules-for-facial-recognition-use-4953506e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>中国周二发布了限制面部识别使用的规则草案，采取措施限制极化技术的扩张，同时为国家安全相关用途留出大量空间。</p><p>互联网监管机构中国网络安全管理局的草案建议将该<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/facial-recognition-goes-mainstream-1537322700?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">技术的使用</a>限制在具有特定目的且足够必要的情况下。这些规则还禁止使用该技术来识别种族、民族、宗教信仰或健康状况——未经科学证明的应用——除非得到个人同意或出于国家安全的目的。</p><p>这些规定使中国对面部识别的私人和商业用途的立场更接近西方规范，包括欧盟和美国地方政府提出的规则。它还为与国家安全相关的技术使用留出了例外情况，这是一个共同特点<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-lays-out-strict-rules-for-chatgpt-like-ai-tools-32f70c89?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">中国的数据和安全法规</a>。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>耶鲁大学法学院蔡英文中国中心高级研究员萨姆·萨克斯 (Samm Sacks) 表示：“在一项法律中，有一些条款反映了一个由技术驱动的独裁超级大国，也反映出对技术滥用的真正担忧。” “这就是中国治理方式的酸甜苦辣。”</p><p>该提案是中国政府采取的一系列举措中的最新举措，旨在限制企业使用数据和人工智能的方式，使其处于全球监管尖端技术的最前沿。 <strong>&nbsp;</strong></p><p>今年早些时候，监管机构对所谓的 Deepfakes、人工智能生成媒体<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-a-pioneer-in-regulating-algorithms-turns-its-focus-to-deepfakes-11673149283?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">实施了规则</a>，并提出了与 OpenAI 的 ChatGPT 类似的生成人工智能工具的其他规则。去年，它开始<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-blazes-hazy-new-trail-to-tame-internets-algorithms-11661866321?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">监管流行应用程序和互联网平台的算法</a>，包括 TikTok 的中文版抖音和无处不在的超级应用程序<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TCEHY" class="">微信</a><span class="company-name-type">。</span></p><p>尽管包括马萨诸塞州在内的一些州和旧金山等城市，但美国没有规范面部识别使用的国家法律<strong>&nbsp;</strong>施加了限制，特别是在执法部门使用该技术方面。在欧洲，政策制定者最近就人工智能法律草案达成一致，该草案将禁止警察和其他国家安全部队在公共场所使用实时面部识别。</p><p>中国的规定也是在中国的新冠疫情控制导致全面采用位置记录和访问控制技术之后出台的。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831490?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">中国已开始监管支撑流行应用程序（例如 TikTok 的中文版抖音）的算法。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Andrea Verdelli/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>研究学者格雷厄姆·韦伯斯特（Graham Webster）是斯坦福大学数字中国项目的负责人，该项目负责研究中国的数字政策发展，他表示，该草案似乎旨在阻止不必要地使用面部识别。他说：“如果得到执行，它将冷却生物识别设备在安全环境之外的扩散。”</p><p>过去七年里，面部识别技术在中国的使用一直在蓬勃发展，使用面部作为身份识别形式的方式在商场、办公楼、机场和酒店如雨后春笋般涌现。中国消费者可以选择在一些商店使用刷脸支付、进入建筑物以及在登机前进行身份检查。</p><p>监控摄像头在中国许多城市随处可见，中国一些最大的面部识别供应商与当地警方建立了合作伙伴关系，提供用于安全目的的技术——不仅追踪罪犯，还追踪异见人士、少数民族和政府认为威胁国家安全的其他人。</p><p>这种技术是国际社会批评北京对待西北地区新疆少数民族群体的批评的核心。中国政府在该地区对突厥裔穆斯林开展了强制民族同化运动。研究人员称，新疆当局使用面部识别和其他监控工具来追踪和分类穆斯林，将数十万人送往拘留营接受政治洗脑。中国否认了这些指控，称其在新疆的政策是为了防止恐怖主义。</p><p>许多中国人或热情或冷漠地迎接智能相机的首次推出，并在日常生活中采用了这项技术。尽管如此，中国领导人对面部识别的广泛使用越来越不满。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-professor-files-rare-lawsuit-over-use-of-facial-recognition-technology-11572884626?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在 2019 年罕见的针对该技术的诉讼中</a>，中国法学教授郭兵指控沿海城市杭州的一家动物园要求他使用面部识别系统才能进入动物园，从而侵犯了他的消费者权利，并且当他不服从时阻止他。法院命令动物园向郭支付赔偿金并删除他的数据，但没有提及动物园继续强制游客进行面部识别是否合法。</p><p>中国南方智库南都个人信息保护研究中心对2019年公众对面部识别的态度进行的调查也发现，普通中国人越来越担心由于缺乏数据安全而导致个人信息被泄露。</p><p>周二拟议的法规将分散在中国各项法律中的对人脸识别技术使用的限制整合到一个框架中，其中包括 2021 年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-set-to-pass-one-of-the-worlds-strictest-data-privacy-laws-11629201927?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">通过的国家隐私法</a>。未经同意即可收集和使用，重申了中国 2017 年《网络安全法》的一个关键方面，即收集个人数据时需要征得个人同意。</p><p>韦伯斯特说，这种冗余的一部分是实用的：明确现有法律应如何应用于面部识别环境。萨克斯说，北京方面还通过这些规则表明它意识到公众的担忧。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831492?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">在中国，面部识别可用于商场、写字楼、机场和酒店的身份识别。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Andy Wong/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>该法规中的一些条款涉及到一些细节，例如，规定不得在酒店房间、浴室或厕所等场所使用面部识别技术，而公众此前曾强烈反对在这些地方使用该技术。它还禁止实体迫使个人采用人脸识别的行为（例如动物园的情况）作为确定其身份的方法。</p><p>与此同时，中国在领导人习近平的领导下一直在扩大国家安全的定义，以涵盖任何被视为破坏共产党统治的事物，习近平为中国可能<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-congress-xi-jinping-us-11665753002" target="_blank" class="icon none">与西方的对抗</a>做好了准备。 7月，修订并收紧的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-expanded-spy-law-adds-to-chilling-effect-of-detentions-ce8cea1a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">反间谍法</a>生效，引起了外国政府和企业的担忧。</p><p>拟议的法规是当局在承认公众辩论和保持对国家安全的严格控制之间游走的最新努力。萨克斯说：“它允许政府通过向公众展示他们正在做出反应来释放压力阀，同时也可以转移对中央当局使用这些技术的注意力。”</p><p>写信给凯伦·豪<a href="mailto:karen.hao@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（karen.hao@wsj.com）</a>和丽莎·林（ <a href="mailto:liza.lin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">liza.lin@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:07:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-drafts-rules-for-facial-recognition-use-4953506e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-drafts-rules-for-facial-recognition-use-4953506e<author><![CDATA[Karen HaoLiza Lin]]></author><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>人工智能/机器学习</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>国家安全措施/政策</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>国家安全措施</category><category>政策</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Legal Assault on Corporate Diversity Efforts Has Begun]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>保守派团体使用许多与扼杀大学平权行动计划相同的工具来挑战亚马逊、康卡斯特和其他公司<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831356/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>埃米尔·伦多夫/华尔街日报<span>埃米尔·伦多夫/华尔街日报</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116214"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116214"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/theo-francis" itemprop="url" rel="author">西奥·弗朗西斯</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/lauren-weber" itemprop="url" rel="author">劳伦·韦伯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 8 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/diversity-equity-dei-companies-blum-2040b173"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>保守派法律活动人士<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/supreme-court-rules-against-affirmative-action-c94b5a9c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">成功挑战了</a>大学使用平权行动。现在，他们正在寻求在美国企业中广泛部署的多元化举措。一些公司已经在重新考虑他们的努力。</p><p>在诉讼、股东信函和向平等就业机会委员会提交的请愿书中，活动人士使用了一些与进步团体用来推进多样性、公平和包容性（DEI）计划相同的策略。他们认为，公司违反了反对种族和性别歧视的规则，包括旨在保护美国黑人权利的立法中制定的规则。</p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CMCSA" class="company-name">康卡斯特</a>解决了一起指控其通过赠款和营销建议非法偏袒少数族裔小型企业客户的案件。<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMZN" class="company-name">亚马逊</a>因一项向黑人或拉丁裔拥有的送货服务承包商额外提供 10,000 美元的计划而在德克萨斯州被起诉。<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SBUX" class="company-name">星巴克</a>董事和高管被股东起诉，称他们支持多元化政策，违反了对投资者的义务。</p><p>数十家公司律师事务所和主要雇主收到了共和党官员的来信，警告他们遵守禁止就业和合同决策中种族配额和偏好的法律。</p><p>爱德华·布鲁姆（Edward Blum）也<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/affirmative-action-supreme-court-ed-blum-100b36c3" target="_blank" class="icon none">组织了这场挑战</a>，最终导致美国最高法院<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/supreme-court-rules-against-affirmative-action-c94b5a9c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">推翻平权行动</a>的决定，他利用最近成立的非营利组织起诉佐治亚州投资管理公司无畏基金（Fearless Fund），指控针对初创企业的资助计划具有歧视性。 Fearless 对有色人种女性经营的企业进行早期投资。</p><p>公司表示，他们的举措符合法律规定。许多人表示，他们仍然致力于增加劳动力和供应商的人口多样性，理由是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-business-case-for-more-diversity-11572091200" target="_blank" class="icon none">商业利益</a>和一些群体在美国公司中继续面临的障碍。</p><p>私下里， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/companiesexpectnew-challenges-todiversitypolicies-after-court-ruling-4bf48c1d" target="_blank" class="icon none">许多人询问他们的律师，</a>根据平权行动的决定，他们是否应该以及多少程度地修改他们的方法。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828205?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">针对亚马逊的一项联邦诉讼针对的是一项向黑人、拉丁裔和美洲原住民送货服务承包商额外奖励 10,000 美元的计划，以支付启动成本。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Kathy Tran/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>许多针对企业多元化计划的法律努力早于高等法院 6 月 29 日的裁决。这项裁决主要针对高等教育招生，并未涉及就业或商业行为。</p><p>但这为保守派活动人士和公职人员挑战企业多元化计划的努力增添了动力。 Companies have long relied on rationales similar to those buttressing affirmative action at universities—that there are benefits to diversity. By dismissing that rationale, the high court weakened the justification for other programs that promote it.</p><p> “Anything a company&#39;s doing that is treating someone differently because of their race, even if it&#39;s a small part of the decision-making process, is going to be scrutinized,” said Dan Lennington, a former Wisconsin deputy solicitor general and deputy counsel for Wisconsin Institute for Law and Liberty, the legal group behind the Comcast lawsuit.</p><p> Employment lawyers say it is likely a matter of time before one of these cases reaches the Supreme Court. Some companies have decided they aren&#39;t going to wait for the court to weigh in. That is especially true for programs that were quickly adopted after the May 2020 killing of George Floyd in police custody, said Angela Berg, who led the global DEI practice at HR consulting firm Mercer and now consults independently.</p><p> Some executives “were uncomfortable with equity programs from the get-go,” said Berg, referring to initiatives such as mentorship or training programs. The Supreme Court has changed the risk calculation, she said.</p><p> Companies are evaluating diversity programs in light of litigation threats that often seem designed to stoke public fear, said Fordham University law professor Atinuke Adediran. She has received inquiries on the subject from an association of human-resources officers at large companies. “Most of what the firms are doing for diversity is legal,” she said. “Companies may need to be ready to defend themselves.”</p><h3> <strong>A Civil War weapon</strong></h3><p> Cable giant Comcast limited a small-business grant program to companies at least 51% owned and operated by someone identifying as Black, indigenous, a person of color, or female—people the company said had been disproportionately affected by the coronavirus pandemic.</p><p> The Wisconsin Institute for Law and Liberty, in suing Comcast in April 2022, cited the 1866 Civil Rights Act. One provision often referred to as Section 1981 says all Americans should have the same rights to sue and enforce contracts “as is enjoyed by white citizens.” The Wisconsin Institute, which says it supports litigation promoting “individual initiative and ordered liberty that leads to prosperity,” essentially turned that section on its head by gathering several white, male business owners as plaintiffs. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="503" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831273?width=700&amp;height=503" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Some activists cite a Civil War-era law that says all Americans should have the same rights to sue and enforce contracts &#39;as is enjoyed by white citizens.&#39; Pictured is a sketch by F. Dielman showing a celebration of the abolition of slavery in the District of Columbia, April 1866.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Library of Congress</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In mid-September, when Comcast announced the next round of grants, it <a href="https://corporate.comcast.com/press/releases/comcast-rise-investment-fund-grants-small-businesses-covid-19-pandemic)" target="_blank" class="icon none">opened the program</a> to all small businesses. Two months later, Comcast settled the litigation.</p><p> A Comcast spokesman declined to comment. In a news release about the program in May, Comcast described the program as evolving “from helping businesses survive the pandemic, to helping businesses and their communities thrive with a focus on economic growth.”</p><p> A federal lawsuit against Amazon.com filed outside Dallas in July 2022 also invokes the 1866 law. It targets a program awarding an additional $10,000 to Black, Latino and Native American delivery-service contractors to defray startup costs. The lawsuit also criticizes an Amazon program aimed at helping Black-owned businesses sell products on Amazon&#39;s website.</p><p> The plaintiff, a Denton County, Texas, resident, wants to apply to start an Amazon delivery-service contractor, but says she won&#39;t until the company eliminates the assistance for minority contractors or offers whites and Asians the same benefit, the complaint says. The plaintiff can&#39;t apply to become an Amazon delivery service partner “without subjecting herself to racial discrimination,” the lawsuit says.</p><p> The case seeks class-action status. It was filed by attorneys including the general counsel of America First Legal, a Washington, DC, nonprofit headed by former Trump administration adviser Stephen Miller. America First Legal describes itself as combating “an unholy alliance of corrupt special interests, big tech titans, the fake news media, and liberal Washington politicians.”</p><p> Amazon has moved to dismiss the lawsuit, saying its selection process for delivery contractors is race-neutral and that the plaintiff doesn&#39;t have standing to sue because she hasn&#39;t applied to be an Amazon contractor.</p><p> In court filings, the company calls her complaint “the epitome of an abstract and generalized grievance by a member of the general population about an internal corporate program that has no actual effect on her.”</p><p> Amazon declined to comment on the lawsuit. “We believe in the importance of diversity, equity, and inclusion,” a spokesman said in a written statement. “We&#39;ll investigate the potential impact of any legal decisions on our programs and adjust as necessary to comply with the law.”</p><h3> <strong>The workplace discrimination argument</strong></h3><p> Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 bans workplace discrimination. The recent affirmative-action decision didn&#39;t address employment practices directly. But Supreme Court Justice Neil Gorsuch in a concurring opinion noted “materially identical language” on discrimination in the laws governing higher education and employment.</p><p> Starbucks officers and directors were sued in August 2022 by National Center for Public Policy Research, a conservative think tank that owns 56 shares in the coffee chain. It accuses Starbucks of violating Title VII and Section 1981, and the officials of breaching their fiduciary duty to shareholders by embracing policies it says violate antidiscrimination law in areas including employment, supplier contracts and executive compensation.</p><p> Under the policies, Starbucks says it wants at least 30% of its workforce at all levels to be Black, indigenous or people of color by 2025. It plans to implement an analytics tool that lets managers see their progress and uses workforce diversity measures to help set executive pay.</p><p> Starbucks and company officials are seeking to dismiss the case, with a hearing scheduled for Friday. They say NCPPR hasn&#39;t shown any real harm from the policies, which are covered by a legal principle that gives company officials broad discretion in running their business, and that courts have upheld diversity policies as permissible. Abandoning them would leave Starbucks vulnerable to other litigation, they say. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="884" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828201?width=1260&amp;height=884" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Starbucks officers and directors were sued last year over policies that involve increasing workforce diversity at all levels of the coffee chain.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Mario Tama/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “We remain committed to creating a culture of warmth and belonging, where everyone is welcome,” a company spokeswoman said.</p><p> In court, Starbucks and its officials also argue NCPPR doesn&#39;t represent shareholders, who have rejected previous proxy proposals from the group suggesting Starbucks favors liberal or “woke” perspectives.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/KO" class="company-name">Coca-Cola</a> is among the companies that has already backtracked. In early 2021, then-General Counsel Bradley Gayton addressed a letter to outside law firms saying that 30% of new legal work for the soda giant should be performed by lawyers who are women, LGBTQ+, disabled or members of racial and ethnic minority groups. Law firms had to report demographic data to Coke, which could cut their fees if the guidelines weren&#39;t met, the letter said. Gayton stepped down from the role three months later.</p><p> American Civil Rights Project, a nonprofit law firm that also represents NCPPR in its Starbucks lawsuit, threatened to sue Coke on behalf of shareholders. In a letter to the company that June, the group called the policies “textbook violations” of Section 1981.</p><p> In early 2022 Gayton&#39;s successor, Monica Howard Doublas, wrote to the American Civil Rights Project that while the company remained fully committed to advancing DEI in the legal profession, she had contacted law firms to tell them the guidelines were never company policy.</p><h3> <strong>A chilling effect</strong></h3><p> America First Legal Foundation, the group backing the Texas lawsuit against Amazon, has written to the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, urging the four current commissioners to bypass the usual complaint process and open investigations into diversity practices at a range of brand-name companies.</p><p> Andrea Lucas, who was nominated to the commission by President Trump, declined to comment on the likelihood that she or other commissioners would open investigations. She said she sees “significant legal and practical risk” in many corporate diversity programs. “Equal opportunity is our charge,” she said of the agency&#39;s mission, “but the law does not demand equal outcomes.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830072?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Bradley Gayton, former general counsel at Coca-Cola, announced new guidelines for the makeup of attorneys doing legal work for the soda giant.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Coca-Cola/Business Wire</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Civil-rights lawyers say conservative activists&#39; arguments distort the original purpose of laws designed to protect groups that, historically, have had fewer labor-market opportunities or difficulty cracking corporate ceilings.</p><p> “The intent here is more political gain and a chilling effect—unfortunately it&#39;s effective,” said Katy Youker, an attorney with the Lawyers&#39; Committee for Civil Rights Under Law, which has been tracking challenges to corporate programs.</p><p> In Florida, a federal judge last year halted enforcement of provisions in HB 7, better known as the Stop Woke Act, which would have restricted private employers from conducting some diversity-related training. The judge said the measures violated companies&#39; free speech rights. Gov. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/ron-desantis">Ron DeSantis</a> &#39;s administration has appealed the decision.</p><p> The pressure leaves employers vulnerable to litigation for either going too far or not far enough in addressing barriers to equity and inclusion, lawyers say.</p><p> “Employers still have obligations to comply with civil rights statutes,” said Charles McLaurin, senior counsel with the NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund. Rolling back DEI programs designed to expand workplace opportunities, he added, “has the potential of creating a hostile environment for certain marginalized groups. Companies would still face exposure.”</p><p> Write to Theo Francis at <a href="mailto:theo.francis@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">theo.francis@wsj.com</a> and Lauren Weber at <a href="mailto:Lauren.Weber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Lauren.Weber@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828197?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The administration of Florida Gov. Ron DeSantis appealed a federal judge&#39;s decision to halt enforcement of elements of what is known as the Stop Woke Act.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Daniel A. Varela/Miami Herald/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/diversity-equity-dei-companies-blum-2040b173</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/diversity-equity-dei-companies-blum-2040b173<author><![CDATA[Theo FrancisLauren Weber]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>wsjillustration</category><category>领导者</category><category>Broadcasting</category><category> Cable Broadcasting</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>Corporate Crime/Legal Action</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>劳工/人事</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Workplace Discrimination/Abuse</category><category> Affirmative Action</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>Discrimination</category><category>教育</category><category>Human Rights/Civil Liberties</category><category>社会问题</category><category>University/College</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> corporate crime</category><category>合法举动</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>workplace discrimination</category><category> abuse</category><category> affirmative action</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>discrimination</category><category>教育</category><category>human rights</category><category> civil liberties</category><category>社会问题</category><category>university</category><category> college</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>broadcasting</category><category> cable broadcasting</category><category>媒体</category><category>娱乐</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Elon Musk Calls Cybertruck Tesla’s ‘Best Product Ever.’ Here Comes the Test.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Truck is expected to hit the market by end of year, two years behind schedule <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116905"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B1A79903-5C46-4C69-8AC4-A0082045E182&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Felon-musk-calls-cybertruck-teslas-best-product-ever-here-comes-the-test-42095f45&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> The launch of Tesla&#39;s Cybertruck is one of the most anticipated EV releases in history. Barclays analyst Dan Levy and AlixPartners&#39; Mark Wakefield weigh in on how Tesla&#39;s first pickup could shake up the pickup market. Photo: Frederic Brown/Getty Images<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116905"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/rebecca-elliott" itemprop="url" rel="author">丽贝卡·埃利奥特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">Aug. 8, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-calls-cybertruck-teslas-best-product-ever-here-comes-the-test-42095f45"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/elon-musk">Elon Musk</a> is seeking to reimagine the classic American pickup with the Cybertruck, a distinctive-looking truck that is all angles and unpainted stainless steel.</p><p> Now, with <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSLA" class="company-name">Tesla</a> expected to debut the truck by the end of the year, the coming months will test whether he can execute on that vision and deliver the company&#39;s first new passenger vehicle in more than three years.</p><p> Bringing the Cybertruck to market has already proven challenging, with years of delays that have included design changes, cost overruns and pandemic uncertainties. The latest twist came Monday when the electric-car maker announced Zach Kirkhorn, who played an important role in keeping company costs in line as CFO, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-finance-chief-zach-kirkhorn-steps-down-44e00ad?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">had stepped down</a> .</p><p> The electric truck was designed to break the mold of a traditional pickup, with a triangular profile and the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-unveiled-a-bullet-proof-pickup-then-the-window-broke-11574444427?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">promise of a bulletproof body</a> . Some industry observers worry the uniquely designed vehicle will have limited appeal to buyers and that the costs of beginning production will hurt profitability as margins are <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-tsla-q2-earnings-report-2023-9be2b571?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">already under pressure</a> .</p><p> Investors are betting the truck will be worth the wait, and that it will inject new excitement into the Tesla brand, which has an older line up than many of its competitors.</p><p> “The Cybertruck is so different, it&#39;ll jazz up the entire franchise,” said Gary Black, managing partner of the Future Fund, a Tesla investor.</p><p> Musk has been hyping the truck for years. He has called it the company&#39;s “best product ever” and has pitched the vehicle as a “badass, futuristic armored personnel carrier” that accelerates like a sports car and is packed with new technology. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831285?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Tesla has taken on manufacturing challenges with the Cybertruck, which uses stronger, heavier stainless steel instead of the sheet metal typically used in car bodies.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Robyn Beck/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In April, Musk said Tesla likely would begin <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-tsla-q1-earnings-report-2023-6b441d30?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">delivering the new pickups</a> in small numbers by the end of September. Output is expected to climb in 2024.</p><p> During the company&#39;s most recent call with Wall Street analysts, however, Musk sidestepped a question about pricing and delivery schedules. Instead, he said deliveries would come this year. He also echoed past warnings that beginning production of a new vehicle can be tricky.</p><p> “The production ramp will move as fast as the slowest and least lucky elements of the entire supply chain and internal production,” Musk said last month.</p><p> Tesla didn&#39;t respond to requests for comment.</p><p> Ramping up production of new vehicles has bedeviled Tesla, where Musk has described the launch of the Model 3 sedan several years ago as “production hell” that nearly killed the company.</p><p> Originally expected in 2021, the Cybertruck began to face challenges almost as soon as it was first shown in November 2019.</p><p> Within months, the Covid-19 pandemic was wreaking havoc on global supply chains and the Cybertruck took a back seat to surer bets designed to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-tsla-q4-earnings-report-2021-11643162910?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">quickly expand Tesla&#39;s market share</a> or <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-to-introduce-upgraded-model-s-to-jump-start-high-end-model-sales-11623334024?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">pad the bottom line</a> , people familiar with the matter said.</p><p> Later, as employees turned their attention to the Cybertruck, they struggled to deliver on their boss&#39;s promises while keeping a lid on costs. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="412" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831286?width=700&amp;height=412" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A Model Y on the factory floor at Tesla&#39;s &#39;Cyber Rodeo&#39; marking the opening last year of the company&#39;s factory outside of Austin, Texas.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jay Janner/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “You can make something infinitely desirable, but if it&#39;s not affordable, that will constrain people&#39;s ability to buy it because they don&#39;t have the money,” Musk said in January 2022, adding that he worried about making a truck that was within reach for Tesla&#39;s customers.</p><p> He initially promised <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-targets-u-s-auto-makers-profit-engine-with-electric-pickup-11574341200?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">three tiers of the truck</a> , starting with a $39,900 entry-level model and topping out at a higher-end version starting at $69,900. He has since said the pricing and specs would be different, citing inflation and “various issues” without sharing specifics.</p><p> The company has taken on an array of new manufacturing challenges with the Cybertruck, which uses stronger, heavier stainless steel instead of the sheet metal typically used in car bodies.</p><p> Tesla aimed to skip an expensive manufacturing step for the outer shell of the truck with stainless steel, which doesn&#39;t need to be painted because it is corrosion-resistant. However, it is rarely used to form vehicle bodies in part because it is less malleable than traditional materials. (DeLorean Motor&#39;s stainless-steel-bodied sports car was featured as the time machine in the “Back to the Future” films.)</p><p> “There&#39;s not industrywide knowledge of how to build stainless steel vehicles, and so there&#39;s a whole bunch of things nobody knows about that they&#39;re going to encounter,” said Doug Betts, president of JD Power&#39;s automotive division.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> And while Tesla excels in areas such as software and powertrain development, it has struggled with the process of building the car body, something the Cybertruck is likely to test, Betts said.</p><p> In addition to reimagining how pickup trucks should look, Musk wanted to upend how they are assembled. He envisioned a vehicle whose outer walls provide much of the overall structure.</p><p> “We moved the mass to the outside. We created an exoskeleton,” Musk said at the 2019 reveal.</p><p> However, Tesla has scaled back its exoskeleton ambitions, pursuing a more traditional vehicle design with an interior structure, people familiar with the matter said. The company did so, at least in part, to meet safety standards, one of the people said.</p><p> Some auto observers had expected more.</p><p> “It&#39;s unconventional in some areas, but for the most part it&#39;s a conventional build,” said Sandy Munro, an engineering consultant who tears apart cars and has reviewed pictures of early versions of the Cybertruck. “It&#39;s not the dramatic change that I was looking forward to,” he said, adding that he still thinks the vehicle will “take the market by storm.”</p><p> Musk has said he expects to make 250,000 or more Cybertrucks a year once output ramps up, making it a niche product in comparison to the company&#39;s best selling Model Y crossover. In total, Tesla sold about 1.3 million vehicles last year and is aiming to sell 20 million annually by 2030.</p><p> The Cybertruck&#39;s delays put it behind in a competitive segment where rivals have already brought their own EV pickups to market. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/F" class="">Ford Motor</a> <span class="company-name-type">&#39;s</span> F-150 Lightning, the top-selling electric pickup, starts at $49,995 after the company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ford-cuts-price-of-ev-f-150-lightning-truck-by-up-to-17-2cc21c6a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">slashed prices last month</a> . Rivian Automotive&#39;s competitor, the R1T, starts at $73,000.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Do you think Tesla&#39;s Cybertruck will ultimately be successful?为什么或者为什么不？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Still, if Tesla can be successful, there is great potential. Full-size pickup trucks are the cash cow of the US auto industry, making up 13% of North American vehicle sales last year while being responsible for about 40% of profits, according to Wells Fargo.</p><p> Analysts expect early efforts to build Tesla&#39;s truck could further erode the company&#39;s profitability.</p><p> But the truck should eventually boost Tesla&#39;s profit margin if the company is able to deliver on its promises, said Anthony Wang, who co-leads the technology investing team at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TROW" class="">T. Rowe Price Associates</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> one of the company&#39;s largest shareholders.</p><p> “Whether the ramp comes this quarter or next, it doesn&#39;t really matter,” Wang said. “What matters more is: Can they execute on the cost and the specs?”</p><p>写信给丽贝卡·埃利奥特（Rebecca Elliott）： <a href="mailto:rebecca.elliott@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">rebecca.elliott@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/e1f7a12e-412d-41e7-b6c1-3f6c0615c7c1.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-calls-cybertruck-teslas-best-product-ever-here-comes-the-test-42095f45</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-calls-cybertruck-teslas-best-product-ever-here-comes-the-test-42095f45<author><![CDATA[Rebecca Elliott]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>机动车</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>汽车</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>特斯拉</category><category>特斯拉</category><category>埃隆·马斯克</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>机动车</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>汽车</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Credit Card, PayPal or Cash App? How You Pay Matters]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> A guide to weighing security, convenience and benefits of each payment option <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001113428"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831133?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Various payment methods provide different conveniences, perks and protections from fraud.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: iStock </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001113428"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/imani-moise" itemprop="url" rel="author">Imani Moise</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 8, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/credit-card-payment-app-fraud-security-3188221b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Buyers have more ways to pay for things than ever before: <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="company-name">Apple</a> Pay, Venmo, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/credit-card-cost-fees-legislation-8782d2e9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">credit cards</a> and dozens of other options. What you choose might matter as much as the purchase itself.</p><p> Each of the different payment methods provides various conveniences, perks and protections from fraud. Credit cards have long been the default option of choice. But <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">higher interest rates</a> have now raised the cost of carrying a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/credit-card-car-debt-payments-behind-decc1a22?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">credit-card balance</a> .</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/teens-venmo-uber-amazon-accounts-5043f9d2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Money-transfer apps such as Venmo</a> and Zelle processed nearly $900 billion last year, and the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau expects that number to reach $1.6 trillion by 2027.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> These apps and services provide easy instant payments, usually for free. The downside is that these options offer fewer protections from <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/jpmorgan-other-banks-in-talks-to-reimburse-scammed-zelle-customers-11669608886?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">scams and unfulfilled orders</a> .</p><p> “The US consumer is very driven by convenience. They may not be directly driven by security,” said James Anderson, managing director at Paze, a bank-owned digital wallet.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dont-forget-to-block-your-ex-on-your-payment-apps-207358bc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Payment apps</a> are among the fastest-growing sources of fraud reports and losses, according to Federal Trade Commission data. Overall fraud losses have increased more than fivefold to $1.2 trillion since 2019. Losses tied to payment apps jumped from $5 million to $47 million over the same period, according to the FTC data.</p><p> As new payment options gain acceptance, consumers should try to educate themselves how to use these methods safely, said Seth Ruden, director of global advisory at BioCatch, a fraud-detection software company.</p><p> “The channel itself is not the villain. The bad actors are the scammers, the social engineers and exploit artists,” he said.</p><p> Here&#39;s how to weigh the security, convenience and benefits of each payment option:</p><h3> Credit and debit cards</h3><p> When you swipe or tap your card or authorize a card transaction online, the merchant&#39;s bank communicates with your bank through a card network such as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MA" class="company-name">Mastercard</a> or <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/V" class="company-name">Visa</a> to ask permission to withdraw a certain amount. Your bank then decides whether to approve the transaction based on your available funds or credit and the likelihood the transaction is fraudulent. If approved, your bank puts a hold on the funds until they are sent to the merchant&#39;s account, usually within a business day.</p><p> Credit cards can be the most rewarding way to pay online. Card issuers use the revenue from transaction fees <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-pandemic-didnt-end-card-rewards-it-made-them-stronger-20fd03c9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to fund perks</a> for customers such as cash-back deals, travel points, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-lounge-battle-royale-coming-soon-to-your-airport-b09cf303?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">access to airport lounges</a> and fraud protection.</p><p> A credit card can be expensive if you don&#39;t pay your balance in full, and higher interest rates have now raised the cost of carrying a credit-card balance. Paying off a $1,000 balance in 12 months at the current average annual percentage rate of 22.16% means $103 in interest, compared with $77 roughly a year ago when the average was 16.65%, according to estimates from the Federal Reserve.</p><p> Debit cards don&#39;t offer the same rewards as credit cards since their issuers make less money from each transaction. They do come with similar fraud and payment protections as credit cards. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="468" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831153?width=700&amp;height=468" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Apps such as Zelle move money more quickly than card payments because the payment is authorized once the sender hits submit.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Tiffany Hagler-Geard/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Federal regulations require issuers to reimburse customers for unauthorized transactions of more than $50 and allow customers to dispute charges within 30 days. Many credit cards also provide purchase protection, meaning you can ask for reimbursements directly from your issuer if something you buy is lost, damaged or inconsistent with what was advertised.</p><p> Few people make the most of their credit-card benefits, payments experts said. After finding most people don&#39;t bother to read the fine print when they sign up for a new card, Mastercard is now notifying customers of benefits in real-time.</p><p> “If I have to read a big booklet or call a number to understand what my benefits are, I&#39;m not doing it,” said Chiro Aikat, executive vice president of US market development at Mastercard.</p><h3> Digital wallets</h3><p> Digital wallets such as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/PYPL" class="company-name">PayPal</a> or Apple Pay are among the safest and easiest ways to pay online. Checking out with a wallet is typically faster than paying with a credit card directly since one doesn&#39;t have to re-enter billing information and shipping address.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Which payment method do you favor, and why?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> All of the protections and benefits associated with the underlying card are still in effect for wallet transactions, so it is best to connect these wallets to a credit card directly to maximize your protection, said Corie Wagner, an analyst at Security.org, a safety-product review site.</p><p> If a digital wallet gives you the option to link a bank account directly, you should read the policy agreement to make sure you understand what is protected. For example, PayPal offers an extra level of purchase protection, but Apple Pay and Google Pay don&#39;t.</p><p> Wallets also offer additional layers of security through encryption and biometric verification and many don&#39;t share sensitive financial data such as your 16-card number with individual merchants. “Use as many authentication factors as possible” such as Face ID or personal identification numbers, Wagner said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=F5C2DBC2-7CEB-4D03-BA48-E58580F05D20&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fcredit-card-payment-app-fraud-security-3188221b&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Tap-to-pay is growing in the US, thanks in part to its security and ease of use. But it&#39;s more complicated than it looks. WSJ takes you inside one of Square&#39;s card readers to break down the tech that powers contactless payments. Photo illustration: Xingpei Shen<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><h3>Peer-to-peer payment apps</h3><p> Apps such as Venmo, Cash App and Zelle were designed to help people send money to friends and family, but they are now used in more settings. They move money more quickly than card payments because, instead of waiting on banks to approve the transaction, the payment is authorized once the sender hits submit. It is almost impossible to get money back once it has been sent.</p><p> These payment methods aren&#39;t regulated as heavily as cards, so users might still be on the hook for unauthorized payments if a swindler gets control of their accounts.</p><p> “Use it to pay people you know, and trust,” said Meghan Fintland, a Zelle spokeswoman. “They&#39;re not meant to have the credit-card security.”</p><h3> Bank transfers</h3><p> Businesses are increasingly offering ways to pay with your bank account directly since Automated Clearing House, or ACH, transfers are much cheaper to process than cards. This option should only be considered in exchange for a discount, payments executives said.</p><p> Consumers should be selective in sharing their bank information with merchants since wire transfers don&#39;t have the same protection guarantees as cards.</p><p> If a business requests a direct bank transfer instead of a card payment, choosing a slower option over the newer instant methods such as Zelle might be best. ACH transfers typically take a few days to settle, giving you a few more days to try to stop the transaction before the money leaves your account.</p><p> “The slower it is, the greater likelihood is that you&#39;ll be able to get recourse,” Ruden, at BioCatch, said.</p><p> Write to Imani Moise at <a href="mailto:imani.moise@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">imani.moise@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/credit-card-payment-app-fraud-security-3188221b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/credit-card-payment-app-fraud-security-3188221b<author><![CDATA[Imani Moise]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>Credit Types/Services</category><category> Credit Cards</category><category> Banking/Credit</category><category>金融服务</category><category>Financial Technology</category><category> Mobile Payment Systems</category><category> Electronic Payment Systems</category><category> Technology</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>Fraud</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>fraud</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>credit types</category><category>服务</category><category>credit cards</category><category> banking</category><category> credit</category><category>金融服务</category><category>financial technology</category><category> mobile payment systems</category><category> electronic payment systems</category><category>技术</category></item></channel></rss>